    "# Exercise 2.19: Exponential Model with conjugate prior\n",
    "\n",
    "(a) Let $y=(y_1, \\dots, y_n)$ with $y_i\\mid \\theta \\sim \\text{Expon}(\\theta)$, and $\\theta \\sim \\text{Gamma}(\\alpha, \\beta)$, then:  \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "p(\\theta\\mid y) & \\propto p(y\\mid \\theta)p(\\theta)\\\\[5pt]\n",
    "& \\propto \\left(\\prod_i \\theta e^{-y_i\\theta} \\right) \\theta^{\\alpha-1} e^{-\\beta\\theta}\\\\[5pt]\n",
    "& = \\theta^{n + \\alpha -1} e^{-(\\beta + \\sum y_i) \\theta}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, $\\theta \\mid y \\sim \\text{Gamma}(n + \\alpha, \\beta + \\sum y_i)$\n",
    "\n",
    "(b) Using the variable change with $\\phi = \\frac{1}{\\theta}$ we get:\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "p(\\phi) & = p(\\theta) \\Big| \\frac{d\\theta}{d\\phi}\\Big|\\\\[5pt]\n",
    "& \\propto \\phi^{-\\alpha + 1} e^{\\beta/\\phi} \\phi^{-2}\\\\[5pt]\n",
    "& = \\phi^{-\\alpha - 1} e^{\\beta/\\phi}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "\n",
    "i.e. $\\phi \\sim \\text{Inv-Gamma}(\\alpha, \\beta)$. Then for its posterior we get:\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "p(\\phi\\mid y) \\propto \\phi^{-(n + \\alpha +1)} e^{-(\\beta + \\sum y_i)/\\phi}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "\n",
    "Hence $\\phi\\mid y \\sim \\text{Inv-Gamma}(n+\\alpha, \\beta + \\sum y_i)$ (cfr. Appendix A).\n",
    "\n",
    "(c) Let $y=(y_1, \\dots, y_n)$ with $y_i\\mid \\theta \\sim \\text{Expon}(\\theta)$, and let $\\theta \\sim \\text{Gamma}(\\alpha, \\beta)$ be such that:\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\text{cv}(\\theta) = \\frac{\\text{std}(\\theta)}{E[\\theta]} = \\frac{\\sqrt{\\alpha}/\\beta}{\\alpha/\\beta} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\alpha}} = \\frac{1}{2}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore $\\alpha = 4$. Now using result from (a), i.e. that $\\theta \\mid y \\sim \\text{Gamma}(n + \\alpha, \\beta + \\sum y_i)$ we can deduce $n$ such that $\\text{cv}(\\theta \\mid y)=0.1$\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "\\begin{split}\n",
    "\\text{cv}(\\theta \\mid y) = \\frac{\\text{std}(\\theta\\mid y)}{E[\\theta\\mid y]} = \\frac{\\sqrt{\\alpha + n}/(\\beta + \\sum y_i)}{(\\alpha + n)/(\\beta + \\sum y_i)} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{n+4}} = \\frac{1}{10}\n",
    "\\end{split}\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "Hence $n=96$.\n",
    "\n",
    "(d) The same computation with $\\phi \\sim \\text{Inv-Gamma}(\\alpha, \\beta)$, leads to $\\alpha=6$ and $n=96$. "
